source_code.code:
private void hideFastView(IViewPart part) {
	// Get pane.
	ViewPane pane = getPane(part);

	// Hide the right side sash first
	if (fastViewSash != null)
		fastViewSash.setBounds(0, 0, 0, 0);
	
	// Slide it off screen.
	Rectangle bounds = pane.getBounds();
	Control ctrl = pane.getControl();
	for (int nX = 0; nX <= bounds.width; nX += 50) {
		ctrl.setLocation(-nX, bounds.y);
		ctrl.getParent().update();
	}

	// Hide it completely.
	pane.setBounds(0, 0, 0, 0);
	pane.setFastViewSash(null);
	ctrl.setEnabled(false); // Remove focus support.
}

Bug.WithStack:
Build: 20020319

OS: Linux 7.2 with Motif

Description:
If I expand a fast view to take up most of the screen, and then minimize it, as
the fast view scrolls across the screen, it leaves behind the right edge.  Once
the scrolling is finished, the screen cleans itself up, but while the view is
scrolling, it's very ugly.  The code that runs the scrolling is in
org.eclipse.ui.internal.Perspective and is as follows:

private void hideFastView(IViewPart part) {
	// Get pane.
	ViewPane pane = getPane(part);

	// Hide the right side sash first
	if (fastViewSash != null)
		fastViewSash.setBounds(0, 0, 0, 0);
	
	// Slide it off screen.
	Rectangle bounds = pane.getBounds();
	Control ctrl = pane.getControl();
	for (int nX = 0; nX <= bounds.width; nX += 50) {
		ctrl.setLocation(-nX, bounds.y);
		ctrl.getParent().update();
	}

	// Hide it completely.
	pane.setBounds(0, 0, 0, 0);
	pane.setFastViewSash(null);
	ctrl.setEnabled(false); // Remove focus support.
}
Not a bug. This is working as expected on the platform.

I spoke with the implementor of fast views about this and suggested that they 
avoid using the animation on platforms other than windows.

Duplicate - this has been fixed.

