Bug.WithStack:
Build 20020319

1) Run eclipse with a new workspace
2) Import->External plug-ins and fragments.
3) Make sure copy and extract are not checked.
4) Next
5) Select all
6) Finish.

7) Import->External plug-ins and fragments. (Again)
8) Make sure only copy is checked.
9) Next
10) Select org.eclipse.ui. (Eclipse Workbench)
11) Finish.

You will get a dialog with the following error:
Problem while importing plugin org.eclipse.ui. Could not set the project 
description for org.eclipse.ui. because the .project file is out of sync with 
the file system.
This looks like a Core bug. The project is first deleted (with the contents). 
Then the new description is created for the project, project is created and 
content is copied into it. WHen the new description is set to the project, it 
complains that .project file is out of sync. It cannot be out of sync when it 
was never there - the project has just been created.

Tips for debugging: 

Place a breakpoint in PDE's ImportOperation.createProject(...) and follow the 
scenario below. The problem sequence is:

IProject project = root.getProject(name);
if (project.exists()) {
   if (queryReplace(project)) {
	boolean deleteContent =
	doImport && root.getLocation().isPrefixOf(project.getLocation());
	project.delete(deleteContent, true, new SubProgressMonitor(monitor, 1));
   } else {
	return;
   }
} else {
   monitor.worked(1);
}

IProjectDescription desc =
   root.getWorkspace().newProjectDescription(project.getName());
if (!doImport) {
   desc.setLocation(pluginPath);
}
project.create(desc, new SubProgressMonitor(monitor, 1));
if (!project.isOpen()) {
   project.open(null);
}

   if (doImport) {
	importContent(
		pluginDir,
		project.getFullPath(),
		FileSystemStructureProvider.INSTANCE,
		null,
		new SubProgressMonitor(monitor, 1));
	} else {
		monitor.worked(1);
	}
        desc = project.getDescription();
	desc.setNatureIds(new String[] { JavaCore.NATURE_ID, PLUGIN_NATURE });
--->	project.setDescription(desc, new SubProgressMonitor(monitor, 1)); 
Here is what happens:

- first project is created in a user-specified location
- first project is deleted (delete contents = false)
- another project is created in the default area
  - this creates a new .project file
- the import tool deletes the .project file 
(ImportOperation.ensureTargetDoesNotExist)
- the import tool imports the content, including existing .project file from the 
source project
- the import tool calls setDescription, which throws an exception because the 
.project file has been replaced from underneath it (by the delete and recreate)

Fixed.  With the new way of listening to changes to .project, the .project file 
that gets imported is discovered immediately, so it is not reported as out 
of sync when setDescription is called.

